%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Energy as the prime example}
\label{sec:energy_as_prime_example}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

It has been argued that energy is the ultimate resource~\cite{library1971energy}
for two important reasons.
First, energy is required 
for extraction of natural resources (including energy itself!),
for any material transformation, 
for consuming goods and services, and 
for disposing of goods.
Second, energy is fungible.
Within the limits of the second law of thermodyanmics, 
energy in one form can be converted to energy in another form
using machines.
An automobile converts chemical potential energy (gasoline)
to kinetic energy (car motion).
A hairdryer converts electricity (from the grid)
to heat (applied to hair).
A solar panel converts solar energy (from the sun)
to electricity (for use in many devices, including, possibly hair dryers).

Because energy is the ultimate resource, 
we use energy as the prime example in the modified Kaya identity.
The question at hand is:
are we using energy at a sustainable rate?

Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph} shows global primary energy consumption through time.

<<PrimaryEnergyGraph, fig.cap="World annual primary energy consumption~\\cite{Roser:2021vi}. ``Other ren.'' is other renewables. ``Nat. gas'' is natural gas. ``Trad. bio.'' is traditional biofuels.">>=
# Gather data for primary energy vs. time graph
primary_energy <- readxl::read_excel(file.path("chapters", "ch05-ResourceIntensity", "datasets", "global-primary-energy.xlsx"),
                                     sheet = "data to plot") %>% 
  dplyr::rename(
    `Other ren.` = Other_renewables_TWh, 
    Biofuels = Biofuels_TWh,
    Wind = Wind_TWh,
    Solar = Solar_TWh, 
    Nuclear = Nuclear_TWh,
    Hydro = Hydropower_TWh,
    `Nat. gas` = Gas_TWh, 
    Oil = Oil_TWh, 
    Coal = Coal_TWh, 
    `Trad. bio.` = Traditional_biomass_TWh
  ) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = -Year, names_to = "primary_energy_type", values_to = "energy_TWh") %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    primary_energy_type = factor(primary_energy_type, levels = c("Other ren.", 
                                                                 "Biofuels", 
                                                                 "Wind", 
                                                                 "Solar", 
                                                                 "Nuclear",
                                                                 "Hydro",
                                                                 "Nat. gas", 
                                                                 "Oil", 
                                                                 "Coal", 
                                                                 "Trad. bio.")), 
    energy_EJ = energy_TWh * 0.0036
  )
  # Make the graph
primary_energy %>% 
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes_string(x = "Year", y = "energy_EJ", fill = "primary_energy_type")) +
  ggplot2::geom_area() + 
  viridis::scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, direction = -1) +
  ggplot2::labs(x = NULL,
                y = "World energy consumption [EJ/year]", 
                fill = NULL) +
  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

By the strong sustainability criterion of consuming resources at a rate 
beneath their regeneration rate, 
none of the fossil fuels shown in Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}
are being consumed at a sustainable rate.
Table~\ref{tab:} shows that 
even byy the weak sustainability criterion of Graedel and Allenby,
none of the fossil fuels are being consumed at a sustainable rate.

